    <h2>📌 Key Decisions & Rationale</h2>

    <div style="background: var(--caution-bg, #fff3cd); border-left: 4px solid #ff9800; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 4px;">
        <ul style="line-height: 1.8;">
            <li><strong>Why Phase 1C (not Phase 2)?</strong> CLI key management is a natural extension of Phase 1B token system - same authentication layer, adds user-facing workflow. Logically grouped as Phase 1C to keep token work together.</li>
            <li><strong>Why Dedicated CLI Tool?</strong> External tools (Grok, scripts, monitoring) need simple, non-browser token management. CLI wrapper reduces friction vs. forcing UI interaction.</li>
            <li><strong>Why Token Scopes?</strong> Principle of least privilege: tokens should only access what they need. Prevents damage if a single token is compromised.</li>
            <li><strong>Why Config File (~/.comserv/credentials)?</strong> Standard practice for CLI tools (like aws, gcloud). Users expect this. File permissions (600) protect secrets from other local users.</li>
            <li><strong>Why 3-Week Timeline?</strong> 21-28 hours of work, parallelized across 2-3 developers (if available), equals ~3 weeks with other responsibilities. Can compress to 2 weeks with full focus.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div>

